<br>
BUT! I'm not suggesting an invasion of the US to disarm them, or instigate a &quot;regime change&quot; (as much as I may like to see one). The reality is that the technology to make weapons of mass distruction, like any technology, is becoming cheaper and easier to obtain. The hardest part of making a nuclear weapon for someone with a large amount of money is probably obtaining the fissionable material, and that can probably be achieved with enough money too. Of course chemical and biological weapons are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> much</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> cheaper and easier to obtain (eg: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.geocities.com/giantfideli/cellnews_dangerous_virus_made_from_mail-order_kits.html">Polio from scratch over the internet: &lt;$10,000</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->). Delivery systems are harder, but a terrorist attack doesn't need to come via a missile.<br>
<br>
The solution cannot be to send in the military to stop these weapons being produced. The solution has got to be to address the problems that cause people to want to use them. It's much harder, and I don't know the answers, but I think it is the only way to go. I think this sentiment, expressed by (Australian Greens) Senator Nettle in her <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.aph.gov.au/senate/senators/homepages/web/sfs-AOR.htm">opening speech</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is a good idea for how to start finding the anwers:<br>
