<br>
There are a few key questions to ask about the current situation.. The answers will provide a clearer perspective as to where we are now and where we are going with this war. <br>
<br>
1. ) Why hasn't the US provided absolute proof? I mean, if you are going to wage a war, and you know with absolute certainty that Iraq has WOMD, and your allies are wanting to know this info, why not give it to them? Why is the US holding out? I know many have mixed feelings in regards to US policy and government, but this is some serious shiit. The proof is coming once all the proper agreements in regards to oil can be resolved....just wait and see. The proof is what will move the rest of the world (or a good portion of it) to support a war....or should I say.. give them reason to support it. <br>
<br>
2. ) Why is Russia so &quot;not sure&quot; about this war? They want weapon inspectors to go back in which is a total waste of time (and a stall tactic until they can be appeased). Russia is using its UN veto power as leverage so that it doesn't get screwed.. Get screwed how? Russia is currently buying oil from Iraq (among other imports and exports) at a ridiculously low price...a Hellofa lot cheaper then Western markets. You cant really blame them... their broke. <br>
<br>
3. ) Why after Bush's little speech before the UN did several Arab nations who were previously totally opposed, all off a sudden tell the US &quot;Yeah, you can now use our soil for your war&quot;? Its because Bush assured the rest of the world we are with the world and not trying to do it all for only us (the US). <br>
<br>
Its as much about each nations own national interest as Desert Storm was about the US's. Its oil and oil prices. Who has it and who controls it. <br>
<br>
Stability: With a loose cannon like Saddam, the rest of the world does not have &quot;security&quot; in their investment (oil). At least in Western eyes.. Every loose cannon provides a potential threat to oil security. <br>
<br>
Another point of contention is Israel. If the US didn't defend and support Israel, most all of the Arab world would be 100% for the US going in to Iraq. Being allied with Israel sets the stage for a possible double-cross. &quot;We like you, but we don't like Israel..and you are allied with her. Our business dealings with you are good, but if Israel ever became a problem, we are not so sure that these business dealings would stay the same.&quot; <br>
<br>
Invest $70 billion in advanced technology so that we are not dependant on oil? Sounds great! I love the idea.. but there is a small problem. Big oil is greedy indeed, but greed or not.. the rest of the world isn't ready. The US could possibly make the quickest and smoothest transition to a AFS. But if the US did it would have a devastating effect on the global economy. The US and rest of the Western world, and its LARGE oil consumption, is what keeps the price of oil down. You wanna start a world-wide shiitstorm? Just decrease US oil usage by 15%.. that should do it. Again, without heavy oil usage, the Middle Eastern oil producing country's would fall into disarray and fast. What else do they to export? Oil is their lifeline. <br>
<br>
Only if the US can and will strike a deal with all concerned country's will it have its war. The US must present this war as an investment in security of finances. <br>
<br>
Which would have a more devastating effect world-wide.. Saddam making small attacks on the US and or western interest.. or the US and western world seizing control of Iraq's oil?<br>
<br>
