I agree that there are differences between the enemies of the USA. I think that Iraq is the nose of the camel in the tent. I really don't relish the idea that my government is directing first strike policies towards its enemies.<br>
<br>
Mass destruction capabilities of a country is <b>not</b> a sound reason to attack it in and of itself. If it were a sound reason, then why stop with Iraq? Furthermore, why not dismantle our own weapons of mass destruction?<br>
<br>
It is a double standard. Because the USA carries the biggest stick our government wants to use it to get its way. I guess I would like to see my government return to the policy that the USA will never be the aggressor.<br>
<br>
I agree that the oil lobby and entrenched politicians are part of the problem and is why the US is not going after altrnative fuels. I will say more below, since Rheaton brings up some excellent points, too.<br>
<br>
<b><i>Rheaton:</i></b><br>
<br>
I think you make a valid point in number 1. However, if the government doesn't present the proof to the people, and attacks Iraq, there will be hell to pay... I am sure of that. The last thing Americans want to see are our troops coming home in body bags and not understanding what they died for.<br>
<br>
Concerning point 2, how do you know the weapons inspectors are a waste of time? It has been 9 years since the UN sanctions against Iraq were implemented. Iraq is hungry. They have very short supplies and are eager to see sanctions lifted. It seems to me that they know they are risking alot by not cooperating with the UN. Iraq certaintly can't withstand another 9 years of sanctions. Also, Saddam is worried about fundamentalists in his country. He doesn't want to see them step up a rebellion and throw Iraq into civil war. In fact, he could be certain that the USA would fully support such rebels and that would wreck his country. I think Iraq has good reasons to cooperate this time. I think the USA should just step back, watch, listen and learn. Sometimes inaction is the best solution.<br>
<br>
Concerning point 3. The Sauds and Kuwait said we can use their bases if a UN resolution allowing for an attack is approved. They will not support unilateral action by the USA and they have made that very clear.<br>
<br>
I agree with you that trimming oil consumption by 15% would be a bad thing for the world economy. I am not arguing that we flip a switch and go over to alternative fuel sources overnight. hehehe<br>
<br>
My point is that our dependence upon OPEC has created a Sh<i></i>it storm for us. We should heavily invest in alternative fuels sooner than later. Oil is a finite resource, and being finite it will disapear one day. Too many of us Americans have no regard for the future of our nation. Many have the attitude that our children will deal with problems of fossil fuel consumption and polution. In the meantime, we can buy the biggest gas guzzling SUV or truck and go four wheeling through Salmon streams and old growth forests with impunity. I don't subscribe to this sort of thinking. I look at my two children and want the best for them. Attacking a country because we want to protect oil so that the CTO of the company I work at can continue to drive his 2003 Hummer SUV is just ridiculous. Some Americans need to grab the lock of hair on the back of their neck and tug really hard to pull their heads out. :)<br>
<br>
<i>"Which would have a more devastating effect world-wide.. Saddam making small attacks on the US and or western interest.. or the US and western world seizing control of Iraq's oil?"</i><br>
<br>
That is a good question, Rheaton. However, I don't know what you could mean by "small attacks". Al Queda proved that a small organization of people can sucessfully attack the USA. While our troops are off galloping about in Iraq the borders of the USA are still wide open for terrorist activity. So, the answer to your question is not to attack Iraq, bring all our troops home and secure our nation's borders against terrorism. Let's put the money into human intelligence and catch the terrorists. Afghanistan should have tought us that bombing and ground searches doesn't deliver up terrorists. Bin Laden is still loose with his millions of dollars.<br>
<br>
Finally, Americans should put pressure on their representatives to force Bush to use the CIA and Special forces to assasinate Hussein; rather than spend billions on the mobilization and occupation of Iraq. I don't doubt for a second that we have the capability to cut off the head of Iraq without sending in a single tank or dropping a single bomb. All it takes is determination and humility. Bush wants to mobilize troops because it will give him and his cabinet media exposure. Everyday a smart bomb drops in Iraq is a good day for Bush's news exposure and ratings. Bush learned that from his father who went into the Presidential elections with a 92% approval rating. However, in the end Clinton won because Bush, Sr. proved to be out of touch with the American people and their needs. GW Bush is the same way.<br>
<br>
I will step off the soap box and give another their turn. ;)<br>
